  "id": "01KVN657YD2TDH2XBYH1HQ08ZE",
  "title": "LurMotorn — BLE Phase A: the cross-platform transport contract",
  "audience": "The developer building LurMotorn (you)",
  "summary": "Phase A of the BLE link (issue #3) — the pure-C++, hardware-free half: the contract both phones must agree on, proven on the host with zero radio. No Bluetooth, JNI, Kotlin, or Mac here; that is Phase B (Android) and Phase D (iOS). The point of doing this first is that both platform backends implement against these exact constants and rules, so getting them right in one shared place stops Android and iOS from silently diverging into a wire incompatibility. Everything here builds and unit-tests via build.ps1 and on the new macOS CI under Apple's clang.\n\nLexicon\n\n**BLE** — Bluetooth Low Energy; the only serverless link that works between an iPhone and an Android phone, so it is LurMotorn's transport.\n\n**GATT** — Generic Attribute Profile; BLE's data model of services and characteristics that a peripheral exposes and a central reads/writes.\n\n**peripheral** — the device that hosts the GATT server (advertises the service, owns the characteristic). One of the two phones.\n\n**central** — the device that scans for and connects to the peripheral. The other phone.\n\n**characteristic** — a single GATT data endpoint; here one writable + notifiable characteristic is the bidirectional datagram channel.\n\n**advertise / scan** — the peripheral broadcasts its presence; the central listens for it. Discovery is symmetric here: both phones do both.\n\n**UUID** — a 128-bit identifier; our service and characteristic UUIDs are the wire identity both platforms must match exactly.\n\n**ITransport** — the engine's platform-neutral 'move bytes to the peer' interface; BLE and the loopback both implement it.\n\n**datagram** — one self-contained message (already minimal); the transport ships it as-is without re-framing.\n\n**loopback** — an in-process ITransport pair used for host tests: one endpoint's Send is delivered straight to the other's Receiver, no radio.\n\n**role tie-break** — the deterministic rule that hands two symmetric peers opposite GATT roles (one peripheral, one central) without any negotiation.\n\n**legal-move index** — the codec sends only a move's position in the deterministic legal-move list, not its squares; both phones regenerate the same list and map the index back.\n\n**CTest** — CMake's test runner; each test is a plain executable that exits non-zero on failure.",
  "generated_at": "2026-06-21T13:33:12.526Z",
